INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1520','letter','1785-06-21','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','','James','Monroe','','Finding from a letter of Mr. Mazzei that you have never been furnished with a copy of the Bill for establishing the Christian Religion in this State, I now inclose one, regretting that I had taken it for granted that you must have been supplied through some other channel.','ltr_mad1520.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1521','letter','1785-07-11','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','','Richard','Lee','','I agree perfectly with you in thinking it the interest of this country to embrace the first decent opportunity of parting with Kentucky, and to refuse with firmness to part with any more of our settlements beyond the Alleghany.','ltr_mad1521.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1522','letter','1785-07-26','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','','Edmund','Randolph','','I have a letter from the Marquis, but dated as far back as March. It was accompanied with a Copy of a French memorial to the Emperor, which seems to have stifled the War in its birth','ltr_mad1522.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1524','letter','1785-08-07','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','','James','Monroe','','Much, indeed, is it to be wished, as I conceive, that no regulations of trade, that is to say, no restrictions on imposts whatever, were necessary.','ltr_mad1524.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1525','letter','1785-08-20','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','','Thomas','Jefferson','','The machinations of Great Britain, with regard to commerce, have produced much distress and noise in the Northern States, particularly in Boston, from whence the alarm has spread to New York and Philadelphia.','ltr_mad1525.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1526','letter','1785-08-23','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','','John','Brown','','I do not smile at the idea of transplanting myself into your wilderness. Such a change of my abode is not, indeed, probable, yet I have no local partialities which can keep me from any place which promises the greatest real advantages.','ltr_mad1526.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1528','letter','1785-10-23','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','','Thomas','Jefferson','','During my stay at New York I had several conversations with the Virginia Delegates, but with few others, on the affairs of the confederacy.','ltr_mad1528.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1529','letter','1785-11-11','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','','George','Washington','','Your letter for the Assembly was laid before them yesterday. I have reason to believe that it was received with every sentiment which could correspond with yours.','ltr_mad1529.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1530','letter','1785-11-15','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','','Thomas','Jefferson','','Mr. Wythe desired me to present you with his most friendly regards. He mentioned the difficulty he experiences in using his pen as an apology for not giving these assurances himself.','ltr_mad1530.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1531','letter','1785-12-09','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','','James','Monroe','','No decisive vote has been yet taken on the assize bill. I conceive it to be in some danger, but that the chance is in its favour. The case of the British debts will be introduced in a day or two.','ltr_mad1531.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1532','letter','1785-12-24','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','','James','Monroe','','The Bill for the payment of British debts is nearly a transcript of that which went through the two Houses last year, except that it leaves the periods of instalment blank, and gives the creditor an opportunity of taking immediate execution for the whole debt','ltr_mad1532.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1533','letter','1785-12-30','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','','James','Monroe','','The past week has been rendered important by nothing but some discussions on the subject of British debts. The bill brought in varied from that which miscarried last year','ltr_mad1533.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1534','letter','1786-01-22','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','','Thomas','Jefferson','','The only one of these which was pursued into an Act is the Bill concerning Religious freedom.','ltr_mad1534.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1535','letter','1786-01-22','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','','James','Monroe','','The bill which is considered at New York as a compliance with the requisitions of Congress, is more so in appearance than reality. It will bring no specie into the Treasury, and but little Continental paper.','ltr_mad1535.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1536','letter','1786-03-18','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','','Thomas','Jefferson','','Since I have been at home I have had leisure to review the literary cargo, for which I am so much indebted to your friendship. The collection is perfectly to my mind.','ltr_mad1536.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1537','letter','1786-03-19','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','','James','Monroe','','The Question of policy, you say, is whether it will be better to correct the vices of the Confederation by recommendation gradually as it moves along, or by a Convention.','ltr_mad1537.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1538','letter','1786-03-19','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','','James','Monroe','','The step taken by New Jersey was certainly a rash one, and will furnish fresh pretexts to unwilling States for withholding their contributions.','ltr_mad1538.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1539','letter','1786-05-12','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','','Thomas','Jefferson','','Your notes having got into print in France, will inevitably be translated back and published in that form, not only in England but in America, unless you give out the original.','ltr_mad1539.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1540','letter','1786-05-13','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','','James','Monroe','','I think, with you, that it would have an odd appearance for two Conventions to be sitting at the same time with powers in part concurrent.','ltr_mad1540.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1541','letter','1786-06-04','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','','James','Monroe','','I expected I should by this time have been on the journey which promises the pleasure of taking you by the hand in New York.','ltr_mad1541.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1542','letter','1786-06-21','Orange','VA','US','James','Madison','','James','Monroe','','I cannot, however, forbear in the mean time expressing my amazement that a thought should be entertained of surrendering the Mississippi, and of guarantying the possessions of Spain in America.','ltr_mad1542.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1543','letter','1786-08-12','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','','Thomas','Jefferson','','My ride through Virginia, Maryland, and Pennsylvania, was in the midst of harvest. I found the crops of wheat in the upper parts of the two former considerably injured by the wet weather','ltr_mad1543.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1544','letter','1786-08-15','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','','James','Monroe','','I did not see General St. Clair, and if I had, my acquaintance is too slender to have warranted my broaching a conversation with him.','ltr_mad1544.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1545','letter','1786-08-17','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','','James','Monroe','','It has occurred to Grayson and myself to propose to Congress that negociations be carried on with Spain upon the following principles: ...','ltr_mad1545.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1546','letter','1786-09-11','Annapolis','MD','US','James','Madison','','James','Monroe','','Our prospect here makes no amends for what is done with you. Delaware, New Jersey, and Virginia, alone are on the ground; two Commissioners attend from New York, and one from Pennsylvania.','ltr_mad1546.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1547','letter','1786-10-05','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','','James','Monroe','','he predominance of temporary and partial interests over those just and extended maxims of policy which have been so much boasted of among us, and which alone can effectuate the durable prosperity of the Union.','ltr_mad1547.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1548','letter','1786-10-30','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','','James','Monroe','','I find, with pleasure, that the navigation of the Mississippi will be defended by the Legislature with as much zeal as could be wished.','ltr_mad1548.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1549','letter','1786-11-01','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','','George','Washington','','The Report from the Deputies to ANNAPOLIS lies on the table, and I hope will be called for before the business of the Mississippi begins to ferment.','ltr_mad1549.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1550','letter','1786-11-01','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','','James','Madison','Sr','Paper money was the subject of discussion this day, and was voted, by a majority of 84 against 17, to be \"unjust, impolitic, destructive of public and private confidence, and of that virtue which is the basis of Republican Government.\"','ltr_mad1550.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1551','letter','1786-11-08','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','','George','Washington','','The intelligence from General Knox is gloomy indeed, but it is less so than the colours in which I had it through another channel.','ltr_mad1551.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1552','letter','1786-11-16','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','','James','Madison','Sr','The House of Delegates have done little since my last, and what was then done is still ineffectual for want of a Senate.','ltr_mad1552.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1553','letter','1786-11-24','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','','James','Madison','','The House of Delegates have just passed a bill making Tobacco receivable in the tax at the market price at the several Warehouses to be fixt by the Executive.','ltr_mad1553.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1554','letter','1786-12-04','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','','Thomas','Jefferson','','The recommendation from the meeting at ANNAPOLIS, of a plenipotentiary Convention in Philadelphia in May next, has been well received by the Assembly here.','ltr_mad1554.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1555','letter','1786-12-07','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','','George','Washington','','In admitting Tobacco for a commutable, we perhaps swerved a little from the line in which we set out. I acquiesced in the measure myself as a prudential compliance with the clamours within doors and without','ltr_mad1555.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1556','letter','1786-12-12','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','','James','Madison','Sr','The inclosed paper will give you a knowledge of the mode and terms on which Tobacco is made a Commutable. It also contains some Resolutions of importance relative to the navigation of the Mississippi.','ltr_mad1556.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1557','letter','1786-12-21','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','','James','Monroe','','We hear nothing from any of the other States on the subject of the federal Convention. The ice seems to have intercepted totally the Northern communication for a considerable time past.','ltr_mad1557.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1558','letter','1786-12-24','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','','George','Washington','','Your observ.ions on Tobacco as a commutable in the taxes are certainly just and unanswerable. My acquiescence in the measure was against every general principle which I have embraced','ltr_mad1558.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1559','letter','1787-01-09','Richmond','VA','US','James','Madison','','Edmund','Pendleton','','The district bill, of which I formerly made mention, was finally thrown into a very curious situation, and lost by a single voice. I refer you for its history to Col. Pendleton, who was here at the time, and is now with you.','ltr_mad1559.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1560','letter','1787-02-15','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','','Thomas','Jefferson','','The principal proceedings of subsequent date relate, as nearly as I can recollect, 1 st , to a rejection of the Bill on crimes and punishments, which, after being altered so as to remove most of the objections, as was thought, was lost by a single vote.','ltr_mad1560.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1561','letter','1787-02-21','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','','George','Washington','','The objects now depending and most immediately in prospect are: 1. The Treaty of Peace. The Secretary of foreign Affairs has very ably reported a view of the infractions on both sides, his exposition of the contested articles, and the steps proper to be taken by Congress.','ltr_mad1561.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1562','letter','1787-02-24','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','','Edmund','Pendleton','','If the contents of the newspapers of this place find their way into the Gazettes of RICHMOND, you will have learnt that the expedition of General Lincoln against the insurgents has effectually dispersed the main body of them.','ltr_mad1562.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1564','letter','1787-03-18','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','','George','Washington','','Recollecting to have heard you mention a plan formed by the Empress of Russia for a comparative view of the Aborigines of the new Continent, and of the N. E. parts of the old, through the medium of their respective tongues','ltr_mad1564.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1565','letter','1787-03-19','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','','Thomas','Jefferson','','What may be the result of this political experiment cannot be foreseen. The difficulties which present themselves are, on one side, almost suflficient to dismay the most sanguine, whilst on the other side the most timid are compelled to encounter them by the mortal diseases of the existing Constitution.','ltr_mad1565.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1566','letter','1787-04-01','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','','James','Madison','Sr','The general attention is now directed towards the approaching Convention. All the States have appointed deputies to it except Connecticut, Maryland, and Rhode Island.','ltr_mad1566.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1567','letter','1787-04-16','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','','George','Washington','','Conceiving that an individual independence of the States is utterly irreconcileable with their aggregate sovereignty, and that a consolidation of the whole into one simple republic would be as inexpedient as it is unattainable, I have sought for middle ground','ltr_mad1567.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1568','letter','1787-04-19','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','','James','Monroe','','No definitive steps are yet taken for the transportation of your furniture. I fear we shall be obliged to make use of a conveyance to Norfolk as soon as one shall offer. I have examined the workmanship of the man in Chappel street.','ltr_mad1568.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1569','letter','1787-04-22','New York','NY','US','James','Madison','','Edmund','Pendleton','','I do not learn that any symptoms yet appear of a return of the insurgent spirit in Massachusetts. On the contrary, it is said that the malcontents are trying their strength in a more regular form.','ltr_mad1569.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1570','letter','1787-04-23','','','US','James','Madison','','Thomas','Jefferson','','The vigorous measures finally pursued by the Government of Massachusetts against the insurgents had the intended effect of dispersing them. By some it was feared that they would re-embody on the return of favorable weather. As yet, no symptom of such a design has appeared.','ltr_mad1570.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1571','letter','1787-05-15','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','','Thomas','Jefferson','','The number as yet assembled is but small. Among the few is General Washington, who arrived on Sunday evening, amidst the acclamations of the people, as well as more sober marks of the aifection and veneration which continues to be felt for his character.','ltr_mad1571.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1572','letter','1787-05-27','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','','Edmund','Pendleton','','Contrary to every previous calculation, the bare quorum of seven States was not made up till the day before yesterday.','ltr_mad1572.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1573','letter','1787-05-27','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','','James','Madison','Sr','Every reflecting man becomes daily more alarmed at our situation. The unwise and wicked proceedings of the Governments of some States, and the unruly temper of the people of others, must, if persevered in, soon produce some new scenes among us.','ltr_mad1573.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1574','letter','1787-06-06','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','','Thomas','Jefferson','','The day fixed for the meeting of the Convention was the 14th ultimo. On the 25th, and not before seven States were assembled, General Washington was placed, una voce, in the chair. The secretaryship was given to Major Jackson.','ltr_mad1574.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1575','letter','1787-07-18','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','','Thomas','Jefferson','','The Convention continue to sit, and have been closely employed since the commencement of the session. I am still under the mortification of being restrained from disclosing any part of their proceedings.','ltr_mad1575.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1576','letter','1787-07-28','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','','James','Madison','Sr','I am sorry that I cannot gratify your wish to be informed of the proceedings of the Convention. An order of secrecy leaves me at liberty merely to tell you that nothing definitive is yet done, that the Session will probably continue for some time yet','ltr_mad1576.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1577','letter','1787-09-04','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','','James','Madison','Sr','The Convention has not yet broken up, but its session will probably continue but a short time longer. Its proceedings are still under the injunction of secrecy.','ltr_mad1577.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1578','letter','1787-09-06','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','','Thomas','Jefferson','','A Government will probably be submitted to the people of the States, consisting of a President, cloathed with Executive power; a Senate chosen by the Legislatures, and another House chosen by the people of the States','ltr_mad1578.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_mad1579','letter','1787-09-20','Philadelphia','PA','US','James','Madison','','Edmund','Pendleton','','The privilege of franking having ceased with the Convention, I have waited for this opportunity of inclosing you a copy of the proposed Constitution for the United States.','ltr_mad1579.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Letters and other writings of James Madison. Vol. I. 1769-1793. Philadelphia, J. B. Lippencott & Co, 1865, digitized by archive.org');
